<font class="body">
<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseTitle">
		<b>Gates Opens International CES with Vision of </b></font></td></tr>
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseSubTitle">
		<b></b></font><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
-->
<tr><td align=left><font class="pressReleaseLocation">
		<b>Las Vegas,NV</b></font></td>
	<td align=right><font class="pressReleaseDate">
		1/6/01</font></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
-->
</table>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0 width=80%>
<tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
	<td><font class="pressReleaseBody"><title>Gates Opens International CES with Vision of ”Extreme Entertainment”</title><title>Gates Opens International CES with Vision of </title>The 2001 International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology  - opened today with presentations defining the status of the consumer electronics industry in a networked world.  During this morning’s opening keynote address, Gary Shapiro, president and CEO of the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA), Congressman Darrell Issa (R-CA), chairman of CEA, and Bill Gates, chairman and chief software architect of Microsoft Corp., each outlined the importance of digital technology in the evolution of the consumer electronics industry.<p>Gates’ remarks focused on the concept of ”extreme entertainment” and the digital lifestyle.  ”Consumer experiences change when we put them in a digital form,” he said, and ”extreme entertainment is a digital lifestyle that changes media itself.”  Gates explained this concept by demonstrating a myriad of consumer electronics products that utilized the power of the PC and software to facilitate flexibility of information access, usage and storage in consumer’s lives.  In demonstrating the next version of Microsoft’s popular Windows operating system software, currently known as Whistler, he described the concept of the ”extended PC” as ”a machine that you will be leaning on 24 hours a day.”   The ”extended PC” is a machine that is always on and serves as the main warehouse for content that it distributes to the rest of the home via any number of different networks.<p>Gates concluded his presentation by unveiling Microsoft’s new XBOX gaming console.  A new venture for the company, Microsoft expects the XBOX to be a tremendous success in the marketplace, as it utilizes the processing power and storage capacity of the PC solely for gaming.  This capacity, he said, ”empowers and unshackles developers” in the development of software for the system.<p>The unveiling of the XBOX was representative of the larger resurgence of the gaming category at CES.  In recent years, gaming has not held a position of prominence at the show, but this year, numerous exhibitors are featuring gaming-related products.  Among the exhibitors with a gaming focus are: Recoton Corp., the industry’s largest supplier of gaming accessories; Dolby Laboratories, which is demonstrating gaming titles in Dolby Surround and Dolby Digital 5.1; and MicroTouch Systems which will host Nolan Bushnell, the ”father of the video game industry,” developer  of ”Pong” and founder of the Atari game company.  Bushnell, also a member of the Consumer Electronics Hall of Fame, will introduce his new venture, Uwink Internet Gaming Tournaments.<p>Shapiro began the presentation by providing a state-of-the-industry overview, highlighting record-setting industry sales in 2000 of $90.1 billion and positive forecasts for the coming year.  ”The digital age is here,” he said.  ”Each year I stand here to talk about the state of the industry, and each year is more exciting than the last.”  <p>Shapiro also presented an outline of the important policy issues facing the industry, including transmission standards and cable must-carry for digital television, sales tax holidays for computer products, adoption of broadband access and copyright protection.  On the issue of copy protection, Shapiro cautioned the audience on the importance of not ”turning the play button into the pay button.”  <p>He concluded his presentation by announcing this year’s inductees into the Consumer Electronics Hall of Fame, and presenting William Kasuga, co-founder and former chairman of the board of Kenwood U.S.A. Corp., with the industry’s Lifetime Achievement Award.<p>Shapiro then turned the microphone over to U.S. Congressman and past CEA Chairman Darrell Issa (R-CA), but first presented Issa with an award of his own, in recognition for his years of service to the association and the industry.  Issa’s brief remarks underscored the importance of recognizing the role of consumer electronics in a global economy, and remaining involved in the political and regulatory processes that affect the industry.  ”I lobbied Congress in my time at CEA,” Issa said, ”and I will be a lobbyist in Congress now.”<p>This year’s CES will showcase the products that facilitate the ”extreme entertainment” that Gates described, as CES features a full range of workstyle and lifestyle technologies.  For more news on CES before, during and after the show, visit www.CESweb.org, the interactive source for CES information.<p>The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) represents more than 600 U.S. companies involved in the development, manufacturing and distribution of audio, video, mobile electronics, communications, information technology, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related services, that are sold through consumer channels.  Combined, these companies account for more than $60 billion in annual sales.  CEA represents the consumer electronics industry in association with the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA).<p>CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, market research and legislative advocacy.<p><br></font></td></tr>



